Date: Wed, 6 May 2026 17:07:50 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 08/14] Use env-driven JWT_SECRET in middleware and
 user.controller

Three different files signed/verified JWTs with three different hard-
coded secrets:
- auth.routes.js     -> 'SECRET_KEY'  (now fixed in previous commit)
- auth.middleware.js -> 'imis_secret'
- user.controller.js -> 'secret123'

Because they didn't match, a token signed at /api/auth/login could
never be verified by middleware on a protected route.

This commit:
- Both files now read process.env.JWT_SECRET, falling back to the same
  dev default the auth route uses.
- middleware now requires a 'Bearer <token>' header (per RFC 6750)
  instead of accepting any whitespace-separated value.
- middleware now distinguishes 'missing header' (401) from 'invalid
  signature' (401) with clearer messages, and 'access denied' (403)
  for role mismatches.
- user.controller.js uses the same JWT shape as auth.routes.js so a
  token from either endpoint passes middleware identically.
- user.controller no longer returns the raw password hash to the
  client (it returned the full Sequelize model previously).
